1
00:00:32,480 --> 00:00:34,480
Before Mats passed away,

2
00:00:36,080 --> 00:00:38,520
he left behind his password for us.

3
00:00:45,480 --> 00:00:47,320
I think this was deliberate.

4
00:00:49,960 --> 00:00:53,040
It was obviously something he had hoped
we would find.

5
00:00:57,120 --> 00:00:59,159
Because behind that password

6
00:00:59,160 --> 00:01:02,280
was a world
we knew absolutely nothing about.

7
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:12,400
I've cracked
a few cases in my time.

8
00:01:16,240 --> 00:01:20,120
Ibelin Redmoore, private investigator,
at your service.

9
00:01:23,320 --> 00:01:26,480
Sometimes you have to jump in
no matter how scary it might seem.

10
00:01:31,680 --> 00:01:34,360
Help us! Come on, please!

11
00:01:35,920 --> 00:01:38,320
Are you
going to stand there all day?

12
00:02:31,680 --> 00:02:33,960
Robert Steen, I love you.

13
00:02:35,240 --> 00:02:36,880
I love you more, you know.

14
00:02:42,160 --> 00:02:46,240
Hi, should we carry you inside?

15
00:03:01,480 --> 00:03:03,159
How lovely.

16
00:03:03,160 --> 00:03:05,320
Do you wanna touch him?

17
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:40,040
We were young parents
and Mats was our firstborn.

18
00:03:41,160 --> 00:03:45,920
He was the most beautiful
and most fantastic boy ever born.

19
00:03:49,360 --> 00:03:54,440
We noticed that Mats developed slower
than other children at his age.

20
00:03:59,320 --> 00:04:04,200
He stumbled more
and he struggled to get up.

21
00:04:06,920 --> 00:04:07,999
We were eventually told

22
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:11,160
that he was born with
a rare muscle disease called Duchenne.

23
00:04:12,440 --> 00:04:16,640
Only boys can get this disease
and mothers are carriers.

24
00:04:17,720 --> 00:04:19,400
And there is no cure for it.

25
00:04:33,280 --> 00:04:35,719
Yes.
We need to hurry up.

26
00:04:35,720 --> 00:04:36,640
Yes.

27
00:04:39,320 --> 00:04:41,040
First day at school.

28
00:04:51,560 --> 00:04:56,240
It's very painful
to see your child get worse and worse.

29
00:04:56,880 --> 00:05:01,279
He was born
with a perfectly functional body.

30
00:05:01,280 --> 00:05:06,039
And slowly but surely you're deprived
of one thing after another.

31
00:05:06,040 --> 00:05:08,199
Then we have Mats!

32
00:05:08,200 --> 00:05:09,599
Come on, Mats.

33
00:05:09,600 --> 00:05:10,840
Come on!

34
00:05:12,440 --> 00:05:14,640
- Shall I help you up?
- Hi!

35
00:05:21,440 --> 00:05:24,679
Raise your arms!

36
00:05:24,680 --> 00:05:28,480
I remember every time
we had to ask for a new aid.

37
00:05:32,320 --> 00:05:34,560
I thought, "Damn, he's at this point now."

38
00:05:38,840 --> 00:05:39,720
That was hard.

39
00:05:40,360 --> 00:05:41,440
Absolutely awful.

40
00:05:53,120 --> 00:05:56,040
All your dreams vanish.
It all goes dark.

41
00:05:59,080 --> 00:06:00,800
Then you have to find new dreams.

42
00:06:03,240 --> 00:06:08,920
We just had to try
to make every day with Mats a nice day.

43
00:06:12,120 --> 00:06:13,879
- You enjoy your swim?
- Yes.

44
00:06:13,880 --> 00:06:15,160
Thumbs up!

45
00:06:17,040 --> 00:06:18,040
Hi.

46
00:06:19,200 --> 00:06:20,999
- Are you having a good time?
- Yes.

47
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:27,199
<i>♪ Happy birthday to you
Happy birthday to you ♪</i>

48
00:06:27,200 --> 00:06:28,600
Hi, Mats!

49
00:06:30,040 --> 00:06:31,360
Happy birthday!

50
00:06:33,120 --> 00:06:34,719
I don't think you know what it is.

51
00:06:34,720 --> 00:06:36,080
I know what it is.

52
00:06:42,720 --> 00:06:45,640
We agreed
to let Mats play a lot,

53
00:06:46,160 --> 00:06:49,000
because of all the other things
he missed out on.

54
00:07:02,520 --> 00:07:06,160
As he gradually became
more dependent on his wheelchair,

55
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:10,560
his gaming time
and screen time increased dramatically.

56
00:07:17,240 --> 00:07:20,359
He would play
when the rest of us were having breakfast.

57
00:07:20,360 --> 00:07:23,960
He would bring the games to school,
and he would play at home.

58
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:35,480
When he had been gaming a lot,
we could see it clearly.

59
00:07:37,160 --> 00:07:39,880
He became tired and he lost his appetite.

60
00:07:40,560 --> 00:07:43,960
He wasn't so bubbly and happy
as he used to be.

61
00:07:54,200 --> 00:07:56,679
I remember
we spoke a lot about Mats

62
00:07:56,680 --> 00:07:58,560
spending too much time at the computer.

63
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:05,479
I tried several times to convince him
to be outside more often,

64
00:08:05,480 --> 00:08:06,840
to do some other things.

65
00:08:10,440 --> 00:08:11,520
There we go.

66
00:08:13,280 --> 00:08:14,360
Now Mia is in the shot.

67
00:08:16,760 --> 00:08:17,880
Let's go and see.

68
00:08:19,520 --> 00:08:20,800
Can he find the ball?

69
00:08:23,280 --> 00:08:26,519
Mum and Dad were really good
at taking us on trips

70
00:08:26,520 --> 00:08:28,360
with other families we knew.

71
00:08:33,720 --> 00:08:35,960
It was fine in the beginning,

72
00:08:36,560 --> 00:08:39,080
but after a while it got harder.

73
00:08:43,160 --> 00:08:46,440
I remember
the day we were going to a concert,

74
00:08:46,960 --> 00:08:50,720
and Mats suddenly decided
that he didn't want to join us.

75
00:08:51,720 --> 00:08:54,559
We had all been looking forward
to this concert for a long time,

76
00:08:54,560 --> 00:08:56,280
so I tried to convince him to come,

77
00:08:59,080 --> 00:09:00,640
but Mats was determined.

78
00:09:02,800 --> 00:09:05,160
He wanted to spend the evening gaming.

79
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:09,359
- Hi.
- Where are you off to, Erlend?

80
00:09:09,360 --> 00:09:11,279
A concert.

81
00:09:11,280 --> 00:09:13,240
- Are you excited?
- Yes, very.

82
00:09:15,360 --> 00:09:16,360
Yes.

83
00:09:19,400 --> 00:09:20,919
- Papa?
- Yes?

84
00:09:20,920 --> 00:09:24,440
He lost touch
with the friends he had.

85
00:09:24,960 --> 00:09:29,280
I can't remember if he really had
any friends in high school at all.

86
00:09:34,840 --> 00:09:38,359
It's really hard to just live your life
and enjoy all the opportunities you have...

87
00:09:38,360 --> 00:09:43,560
...when one of the people
you love the most gets fewer and fewer...

88
00:09:44,880 --> 00:09:45,880
opportunities.

89
00:09:49,320 --> 00:09:51,040
It's midnight.

90
00:09:51,920 --> 00:09:53,120
Sleep well, my boy.

91
00:09:54,960 --> 00:09:57,960
No thanks. Last test.

92
00:09:59,320 --> 00:10:00,640
It's getting exciting.

93
00:10:05,280 --> 00:10:06,440
I'm just closing it.

94
00:10:13,800 --> 00:10:16,479
When Mats
finished high school, he moved out.

95
00:10:16,480 --> 00:10:17,920
And he loved it.

96
00:10:19,440 --> 00:10:22,439
Even though he only moved
to the first floor of our house,

97
00:10:22,440 --> 00:10:24,520
he enjoyed his independence.

98
00:10:27,080 --> 00:10:30,440
One of the first things he did
was to hang up a picture he loved.

99
00:10:31,720 --> 00:10:33,560
He also started writing a blog.

100
00:10:38,720 --> 00:10:40,879
He had special equipment made for him.

101
00:10:40,880 --> 00:10:44,240
I can go backwards
while I do that, see?

102
00:10:45,440 --> 00:10:47,559
Bang, bang, bang, you can hop to the side.

103
00:10:47,560 --> 00:10:50,080
- And then keep shooting.
- I see.

104
00:10:50,800 --> 00:10:53,959
It's amazing what
the makers of this game come up with.

105
00:10:53,960 --> 00:10:56,719
- Mmm.
- They're creating a whole digital world.

106
00:10:56,720 --> 00:10:57,640
Right.

107
00:10:58,200 --> 00:11:01,880
Mats told us
that he was gaming with other people.

108
00:11:04,360 --> 00:11:07,560
But we thought
that these people didn't know Mats

109
00:11:08,080 --> 00:11:11,000
because they never met physically,
and they never talked.

110
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:17,959
And during his last ten years,

111
00:11:17,960 --> 00:11:21,560
he probably spent 20,000 hours
in this gaming world.

112
00:11:42,720 --> 00:11:45,000
His world seemed so limited.

113
00:11:47,760 --> 00:11:52,320
If you're gaming 12 hours a day,
you don't have time for anything else.

114
00:11:53,920 --> 00:11:56,120
You don't have time to meet your friends.

115
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:05,719
Our deepest sorrow lay in the fact

116
00:12:05,720 --> 00:12:10,440
that he would
never experience friendships, love,

117
00:12:11,040 --> 00:12:13,840
or to make a difference
in other people's lives.

118
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:28,279
The last video recording of Mats

119
00:12:28,280 --> 00:12:31,160
was taken during his uncle's wedding.

120
00:13:10,760 --> 00:13:13,480
He just fell asleep,
and then he was gone.

121
00:13:14,920 --> 00:13:16,000
And then it was over.

122
00:13:26,560 --> 00:13:30,320
You can never fully prepare
for losing a child.

123
00:13:35,200 --> 00:13:37,640
He and I fought,

124
00:13:38,960 --> 00:13:41,120
and struggled, and I think I often felt

125
00:13:41,880 --> 00:13:43,720
that it was my fault

126
00:13:44,640 --> 00:13:46,200
that he was born this way.

127
00:13:49,360 --> 00:13:52,839
I mean, we had a bond that was so...
it was so strong.

128
00:13:52,840 --> 00:13:55,480
And I lived and breathed for that boy.

129
00:14:00,120 --> 00:14:02,999
Then it was as if time stood still
over the next few days.

130
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:05,959
We just
sat on the couch and cried,

131
00:14:05,960 --> 00:14:08,040
and people came and went, and then...

132
00:14:08,560 --> 00:14:09,800
It was just so strange.

133
00:14:11,520 --> 00:14:14,200
When I walked past
his apartment with all his things...

134
00:14:15,920 --> 00:14:18,120
Seeing the wheelchair
without someone in it...

135
00:14:19,360 --> 00:14:20,480
It was so strange.

136
00:14:21,640 --> 00:14:22,480
Yeah.

137
00:14:25,280 --> 00:14:28,639
And there we were, Robert, and Mia, and I,

138
00:14:28,640 --> 00:14:31,919
sitting on the couch
for what felt like at least 24 hours.

139
00:14:31,920 --> 00:14:35,719
And we couldn't sleep,
so everything just became a blur.

140
00:14:35,720 --> 00:14:38,839
When we'd gathered our thoughts a little,

141
00:14:38,840 --> 00:14:42,239
we started thinking,
"Oh my God, we need to

142
00:14:42,240 --> 00:14:43,759
tell people online."

143
00:14:43,760 --> 00:14:46,160
They have to know
that he won't be logging on.

144
00:14:47,040 --> 00:14:49,440
And then we thought,
"How do we do that, then?"

145
00:14:52,240 --> 00:14:56,200
And Robert suddenly remembered,
"I have the password to Mats's blog."

146
00:14:57,000 --> 00:14:59,239
"Maybe I can try that."

147
00:14:59,240 --> 00:15:01,760
"I don't think it has a wide reach,
but I'll try anyway."

148
00:15:04,320 --> 00:15:08,840
And then he sat down,
and together, we wrote that text.

149
00:15:30,920 --> 00:15:33,679
And then we just sent it "out in space."

150
00:15:33,680 --> 00:15:37,520
We didn't know
if anyone would see it at all.

151
00:16:10,440 --> 00:16:14,039
And then,
we got email after email.

152
00:16:14,040 --> 00:16:15,480
We were so confused.

153
00:16:17,400 --> 00:16:19,199
What is this?

154
00:16:19,200 --> 00:16:21,559
Who are these people?

155
00:16:21,560 --> 00:16:24,240
Are they completely crazy or what?

156
00:16:40,960 --> 00:16:42,519
Many people wrote a lot.

157
00:16:42,520 --> 00:16:44,400
It was out of control.

158
00:16:53,880 --> 00:16:56,400
<i>Dear Robert, Trude, and Mia...</i>

159
00:17:08,440 --> 00:17:11,680
<i>Mats was a real friend to me.</i>

160
00:17:15,400 --> 00:17:18,000
<i>He was an incurable romantic</i>

161
00:17:19,240 --> 00:17:21,400
<i>and had considerable success with women.</i>

162
00:17:24,040 --> 00:17:28,560
<i>He would always throw,
like, a comment to lighten the mood.</i>

163
00:17:33,960 --> 00:17:36,079
<i>If you told him
you were going to see a movie,</i>

164
00:17:36,080 --> 00:17:38,760
<i>he would remember
that you saw that movie later.</i>

165
00:17:40,280 --> 00:17:42,239
<i>He would listen, and then, like...</i>

166
00:17:42,240 --> 00:17:45,479
<i>I'm remembering, back then,
that he was there for me,</i>

167
00:17:45,480 --> 00:17:48,200
<i>and I could also talk to him
about the stupid things.</i>

168
00:17:50,480 --> 00:17:54,640
<i>And I feel almost like
he was part of the family.</i>

169
00:17:58,040 --> 00:18:01,480
<i>You always knew that
when he told you something, he meant it.</i>

170
00:18:07,920 --> 00:18:10,839
<i>And I don't think he was aware</i>

171
00:18:10,840 --> 00:18:15,000
<i>of how big an impact
he had done to a lot of people.</i>

172
00:19:49,400 --> 00:19:51,120
<i>I was born in 1989,</i>

173
00:19:52,000 --> 00:19:54,040
<i>just in time to avoid most of the '80s.</i>

174
00:20:01,480 --> 00:20:04,199
<i>Well, there was
some sweet music from that decade,</i>

175
00:20:04,200 --> 00:20:06,399
<i>but the fashion
and the style was terrible.</i>

176
00:20:06,400 --> 00:20:09,639
<i>Shoulder pads, strange hairdos,</i>

177
00:20:09,640 --> 00:20:11,520
<i>and those dreaded pastel colours.</i>

178
00:20:13,920 --> 00:20:16,920
<i>I know some like this style
for reasons that are beyond me.</i>

179
00:20:19,120 --> 00:20:21,360
<i>It was the year the Berlin Wall crumbled.</i>

180
00:20:25,720 --> 00:20:27,640
<i>Not that I recall anything about that.</i>

181
00:20:31,760 --> 00:20:33,039
<i>I like that thought.</i>

182
00:20:33,040 --> 00:20:36,080
<i>As if the wall had to come down
because I would be born.</i>

183
00:20:42,080 --> 00:20:45,760
<i>I had just got
my first real electrical wheelchair.</i>

184
00:20:47,520 --> 00:20:50,960
<i>With four large tires,
it was built for almost all terrain.</i>

185
00:20:51,760 --> 00:20:52,960
<i>Quite impressive, huh?</i>

186
00:20:53,960 --> 00:20:56,079
<i>It was called The Exterior,</i>

187
00:20:56,080 --> 00:20:58,280
<i>and we had many adventures together.</i>

188
00:20:59,360 --> 00:21:02,679
<i>That chair was so cool
that when I drove through the school yard,</i>

189
00:21:02,680 --> 00:21:05,839
<i>a younger kid would roll up next to me
on his tricycle,</i>

190
00:21:05,840 --> 00:21:08,399
<i>look up at me with big eyes and ask,</i>

191
00:21:08,400 --> 00:21:09,680
<i>"Do you want to trade?"</i>

192
00:21:10,880 --> 00:21:13,199
<i>Sure, I'll gladly trade you my chair.</i>

193
00:21:13,200 --> 00:21:15,280
<i>It comes with a muscular condition.</i>

194
00:21:16,040 --> 00:21:19,520
<i>Then I'd happily roll away
on my brand new tricycle into the sunset.</i>

195
00:21:23,720 --> 00:21:26,760
<i>I was sent to summer camp
with other handicapped kids.</i>

196
00:21:28,680 --> 00:21:30,240
<i>I hated the entire idea.</i>

197
00:21:32,640 --> 00:21:34,839
<i>The biggest issue
I had with the camp</i>

198
00:21:34,840 --> 00:21:36,640
<i>was the trip to an amusement park.</i>

199
00:21:38,400 --> 00:21:40,960
<i>Parading in there
like some kind of freak show.</i>

200
00:21:42,440 --> 00:21:45,760
<i>It was like some twisted,
handicap version of</i> Prison Break<i>.</i>

201
00:21:47,160 --> 00:21:49,320
<i>I started thinking of ways I could escape.</i>

202
00:21:51,080 --> 00:21:53,040
<i>The other people would stare.</i>

203
00:21:53,720 --> 00:21:56,839
<i>They always talked in big, easy words.</i>

204
00:21:56,840 --> 00:21:59,360
<i>"Hello. Do you like the park?"</i>

205
00:22:00,120 --> 00:22:03,680
<i>Yeah, I'm not deaf or mentally challenged,
thank you very much.</i>

206
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:12,000
<i>I have a lovely apartment
and a loving family nearby.</i>

207
00:22:13,520 --> 00:22:15,440
<i>I don't work as I don't need to.</i>

208
00:22:17,040 --> 00:22:18,720
<i>"Lucky bugger," some might think.</i>

209
00:22:19,520 --> 00:22:21,600
<i>I have my own reasons for this.</i>

210
00:22:23,480 --> 00:22:25,600
<i>Suddenly this sounds like a contact ad.</i>

211
00:22:26,400 --> 00:22:28,599
<i>Soon, I'll write about
long walks on the beach</i>

212
00:22:28,600 --> 00:22:30,480
<i>and how great I am at listening.</i>

213
00:22:32,400 --> 00:22:33,680
<i>No, you can relax.</i>

214
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:40,880
<i>We won't go there in this entry.</i>

215
00:22:51,200 --> 00:22:53,320
<i>Luckily, I have found my escape.</i>

216
00:22:58,040 --> 00:22:59,399
<i>It's not a screen.</i>

217
00:22:59,400 --> 00:23:02,040
<i>It's a gateway
to wherever your heart desires.</i>

218
00:23:04,120 --> 00:23:07,600
<i>I boot up the computer, music pumping.</i>

219
00:23:09,120 --> 00:23:10,800
<i>And then, I leave this world.</i>

220
00:23:13,480 --> 00:23:18,559
<i>♪ With nothing to say
We're ghosts that occupy a space ♪</i>

221
00:23:18,560 --> 00:23:20,440
<i>♪ Barely here ♪</i>

222
00:23:21,320 --> 00:23:26,439
<i>♪ We're starting to rust
The hurt is spilling out of us ♪</i>

223
00:23:26,440 --> 00:23:28,560
<i>♪ Through the tears ♪</i>

224
00:23:29,240 --> 00:23:34,039
<i>♪ This fragile affair
Is turning into solitaire ♪</i>

225
00:23:34,040 --> 00:23:36,040
<i>♪ We're full of the air ♪</i>

226
00:23:37,040 --> 00:23:42,039
<i>♪ We need to adjust
We're losing every part of us ♪</i>

227
00:23:42,040 --> 00:23:44,039
<i>♪ We disappear ♪</i>

228
00:23:44,040 --> 00:23:47,559
<i>♪ Faith, where have you gone? ♪</i>

229
00:23:47,560 --> 00:23:51,520
<i>♪ Was it me that made it all wrong? ♪</i>

230
00:23:52,160 --> 00:23:55,280
<i>♪ Faith, where have you gone... ♪</i>

231
00:23:56,200 --> 00:23:59,320
<i>I spend most of my time
in a little place called Azeroth.</i>

232
00:24:00,920 --> 00:24:03,040
<i>In there, my chains are broken.</i>

233
00:24:04,720 --> 00:24:06,600
<i>And I can be whoever I want to be.</i>

234
00:24:17,440 --> 00:24:20,520
<i>I'm Ibelin Redmoore,
famed detective and nobleman.</i>

235
00:24:23,760 --> 00:24:25,119
<i>He fights forces of evil,</i>

236
00:24:25,120 --> 00:24:27,520
<i>and makes friends and enemies
wherever he goes.</i>

237
00:24:33,440 --> 00:24:36,359
<i>Ibelin is expansions of myself.</i>

238
00:24:36,360 --> 00:24:39,159
<i>Different parts of me.</i>

239
00:24:39,160 --> 00:24:41,639
<i>♪ Faith, where have you gone... ♪</i>

240
00:24:41,640 --> 00:24:44,479
<i>A good thing about virtual beer
is that you don't get drunk.</i>

241
00:24:44,480 --> 00:24:46,280
<i>You just pretend you did.</i>

242
00:24:48,480 --> 00:24:50,000
<i>It must sound absurd,</i>

243
00:24:50,840 --> 00:24:52,840
<i>but a fun challenge for a roleplayer.</i>

244
00:24:54,680 --> 00:24:58,119
<i>♪ And faith, where have you gone? ♪</i>

245
00:24:58,120 --> 00:25:01,520
<i>♪ Lord, give me faith so I can be... ♪</i>

246
00:25:10,880 --> 00:25:13,160
<i>In real life,
I need to keep positive,</i>

247
00:25:13,960 --> 00:25:17,160
<i>fight the hardships,
and emerge with a smile on my lips.</i>

248
00:25:25,400 --> 00:25:27,720
<i>There were so many things
I had missed out on.</i>

249
00:25:35,120 --> 00:25:38,720
<i>Friends I could have made if I had
just forced myself to be more social.</i>

250
00:25:39,920 --> 00:25:42,160
<i>I guess I'll always be a bit shy that way.</i>

251
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:53,800
<i>In high school, there were parties,</i>

252
00:25:56,400 --> 00:25:57,480
<i>attractive girls,</i>

253
00:25:58,920 --> 00:26:03,000
<i>mopeds,
so many things a boy at 17 desired,</i>

254
00:26:04,400 --> 00:26:06,320
<i>but they were all just dreams.</i>

255
00:26:08,520 --> 00:26:10,400
<i>Things beyond my reach.</i>

256
00:26:15,960 --> 00:26:18,759
<i>Just as I was about to pick up
the cutest girl in school</i>

257
00:26:18,760 --> 00:26:20,200
<i>and drive some place romantic,</i>

258
00:26:21,360 --> 00:26:23,080
<i>I was ripped out of my fantasy.</i>

259
00:26:31,080 --> 00:26:32,600
<i>Dreams are nice that way.</i>

260
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:35,640
<i>You can always visit again.</i>

261
00:26:40,600 --> 00:26:42,679
<i>Good thing I'm chained to this wheelchair</i>

262
00:26:42,680 --> 00:26:45,040
<i>or I'd be out
giving my mother a heart attack,</i>

263
00:26:45,640 --> 00:26:48,120
<i>thundering down the road
on a motorbike of my own.</i>

264
00:26:59,720 --> 00:27:01,600
<i>Dear Trude, Robert, and Mia,</i>

265
00:27:02,920 --> 00:27:05,800
<i>I'm a friend of Mats,
and I knew him through Ibelin.</i>

266
00:27:09,120 --> 00:27:11,159
<i>I am the leader of Starlight,</i>

267
00:27:11,160 --> 00:27:15,440
<i>the community of friends
Ibelin was a member of for eight years.</i>

268
00:27:17,200 --> 00:27:22,440
<i>We meet each other through avatars,
and behind each of them is a real person.</i>

269
00:27:29,280 --> 00:27:30,960
<i>And together, we roleplay.</i>

270
00:27:31,560 --> 00:27:35,319
<i>The player adapts a role
and guides that role through adventures,</i>

271
00:27:35,320 --> 00:27:37,000
<i>trials, and tribulations.</i>

272
00:27:42,240 --> 00:27:45,559
<i>Roleplay at its core
is simply playing a role.</i>

273
00:27:45,560 --> 00:27:48,480
<i>We choose what our avatar
should say and do.</i>

274
00:27:51,640 --> 00:27:56,400
<i>Since Ibelin was very private, we knew
almost nothing about him in real life.</i>

275
00:27:57,520 --> 00:28:01,000
<i>All the communication we had with him
were done through text.</i>

276
00:28:02,240 --> 00:28:06,080
<i>And many of these texts were logged
and stored while we were gaming.</i>

277
00:28:11,800 --> 00:28:14,119
<i>They were published publicly
on our forums,</i>

278
00:28:14,120 --> 00:28:16,920
<i>but they weren't
easy to find for most people.</i>

279
00:28:18,320 --> 00:28:20,679
<i>These texts contain gaming dialogue,</i>

280
00:28:20,680 --> 00:28:24,839
<i>character diaries,
and forum discussions from our community.</i>

281
00:28:24,840 --> 00:28:27,680
<i>In total, 42,000 pages.</i>

282
00:28:32,600 --> 00:28:34,079
<i>So when Mats wrote,</i>

283
00:28:34,080 --> 00:28:37,719
<i>"I'm an emotional man,
I often follow my heart,"</i>

284
00:28:37,720 --> 00:28:41,160
<i>we know that he wrote this
the 30th of August 2012.</i>

285
00:28:43,240 --> 00:28:46,440
<i>We know the location
and what was said by those with him.</i>

286
00:28:52,720 --> 00:28:56,040
<i>Ibelin's feelings and actions
are also in the archive.</i>

287
00:30:06,120 --> 00:30:07,800
A good game of football.

288
00:30:12,120 --> 00:30:14,360
- This soup is amazing.
- Yeah!

289
00:30:25,480 --> 00:30:27,960
<i>It was a peaceful,
warm evening in Azeroth.</i>

290
00:30:28,640 --> 00:30:32,240
<i>Sitting around the campfire
enjoying some drinks and good stories.</i>

291
00:30:46,480 --> 00:30:48,239
<i>While we were sitting there,</i>

292
00:30:48,240 --> 00:30:51,480
<i>a dark-haired, mysterious beauty
comes out of the woods.</i>

293
00:31:01,600 --> 00:31:03,839
<i>I'm not sure how it happened,</i>

294
00:31:03,840 --> 00:31:06,640
<i>but she started teasing
and flirting with my character.</i>

295
00:31:08,280 --> 00:31:09,520
<i>And I liked it.</i>

296
00:31:12,480 --> 00:31:15,880
<i>My character just sat there,
clueless of what to do next.</i>

297
00:31:18,120 --> 00:31:20,960
She's flirting with you.
You should go after her.

298
00:31:21,640 --> 00:31:25,080
Tss. No, no, she is not flirting with me.

299
00:31:25,640 --> 00:31:27,560
She's clearly into you.

300
00:31:28,600 --> 00:31:29,520
Hmm.

301
00:31:36,480 --> 00:31:38,720
<i>♪ Another club craze ♪</i>

302
00:31:39,920 --> 00:31:43,039
<i>♪ Brings out some weird, vivid sights... ♪</i>

303
00:31:43,040 --> 00:31:45,000
<i>Eventually, Ibelin got up,</i>

304
00:31:45,800 --> 00:31:47,840
<i>and he followed the mysterious woman.</i>

305
00:31:50,960 --> 00:31:52,319
<i>That's how it began.</i>

306
00:31:52,320 --> 00:31:58,239
<i>♪ So I run till the sea surrounds me ♪</i>

307
00:31:58,240 --> 00:32:02,720
<i>♪ And the palms cover ♪</i>

308
00:32:09,440 --> 00:32:11,400
<i>♪ You're so tempered ♪</i>

309
00:32:12,640 --> 00:32:16,079
<i>♪ That's why I don't know
I'm in my mind ♪</i>

310
00:32:16,080 --> 00:32:18,680
<i>♪ I just intended to ♪</i>

311
00:32:21,400 --> 00:32:24,000
<i>There was something
very exciting about her.</i>

312
00:32:25,520 --> 00:32:28,160
<i>Her humour, the way she acted.</i>

313
00:32:29,480 --> 00:32:30,680
<i>I was sold.</i>

314
00:32:52,400 --> 00:32:55,400
...see what they're on about,
so I did.

315
00:33:20,440 --> 00:33:21,839
...that can be uprooted with ease.

316
00:33:21,840 --> 00:33:26,479
<i>In real life, I was 17 at the time,
no idea how to even approach a girl.</i>

317
00:33:26,480 --> 00:33:29,999
I've never been drinking more
at any point in my life than I do now,

318
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:33,759
and even though one mug
might not be so bad,

319
00:33:33,760 --> 00:33:35,759
the dumb bartenders keep refilling it,

320
00:33:35,760 --> 00:33:38,639
so at the end of the evening,
you can't be sure how much you've had!

321
00:33:38,640 --> 00:33:41,439
I really need to find a different...

322
00:33:41,440 --> 00:33:45,080
<i>Luckily, pretty much every character
in this virtual world looked great.</i>

323
00:33:46,680 --> 00:33:48,279
<i>Many might find this silly,</i>

324
00:33:48,280 --> 00:33:50,679
<i>but at least
looks don't matter much anymore.</i>

325
00:33:50,680 --> 00:33:52,240
<i>It's all about personality.</i>

326
00:33:52,800 --> 00:33:57,239
I'm starting up my business again,
even got my first client yesterday.

327
00:33:57,240 --> 00:34:01,679
I've cracked a few cases in my time.
It's a small agency.

328
00:34:01,680 --> 00:34:02,640
Here.

329
00:34:02,641 --> 00:34:04,600
An old business card.

330
00:34:05,360 --> 00:34:07,880
You should just go out there
and spread these around.

331
00:34:08,400 --> 00:34:12,160
Ibelin Redmoore, private investigator,
at your service.

332
00:35:02,320 --> 00:35:04,480
<i>It was just a virtual kiss.</i>

333
00:35:08,640 --> 00:35:10,760
<i>But, boy, I could almost feel it.</i>

334
00:35:17,400 --> 00:35:21,960
<i>It was the closest thing I've ever been
to a crush in my entire life.</i>

335
00:35:44,640 --> 00:35:45,800
<i>It was amazing.</i>

336
00:36:23,120 --> 00:36:24,600
Oh.

337
00:36:44,760 --> 00:36:47,400
You eventually get tired
of throwing stones all night.

338
00:36:49,000 --> 00:36:50,519
The world's going crazy, I tell you.

339
00:36:50,520 --> 00:36:53,119
Just need to keep going and stay busy.

340
00:36:53,120 --> 00:36:54,320
All that talk about...

341
00:38:19,920 --> 00:38:21,320
<i>She just disappeared.</i>

342
00:38:33,160 --> 00:38:35,040
<i>She had to be around somewhere.</i>

343
00:38:48,200 --> 00:38:51,000
<i>Wherever you are, Rumour,
you are always with me.</i>

344
00:39:43,080 --> 00:39:46,360
I was walking around
in Elwynn Forest near Goldshire.

345
00:39:51,160 --> 00:39:52,600
This soup is amazing.

346
00:39:53,120 --> 00:39:56,119
And then I saw
two people sitting around a campfire

347
00:39:56,120 --> 00:39:57,400
back at the lake.

348
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:13,239
And I just thought,

349
00:40:13,240 --> 00:40:15,519
"I've just gotta steal the hat
and see what happens."

350
00:40:15,520 --> 00:40:20,599
There was no real much pre-thought
or plotting or planning around it

351
00:40:20,600 --> 00:40:23,040
apart from, "I'm just gonna do it
and see what happens."

352
00:40:26,200 --> 00:40:29,319
We had the whole,
"Let's go on a date together,"

353
00:40:29,320 --> 00:40:31,040
and he would give the flowers.

354
00:40:31,560 --> 00:40:32,480
Um...

355
00:40:32,481 --> 00:40:35,519
It's a slightly cheesy,
but still nice kind of thing.

356
00:40:35,520 --> 00:40:38,439
Every girl always says,
"No, I don't really need flowers,"

357
00:40:38,440 --> 00:40:40,920
but we really love it
when we still get them.

358
00:40:53,840 --> 00:40:56,319
I never got to see him
because he...

359
00:40:56,320 --> 00:41:01,040
he didn't want to, like, video call
or share his camera.

360
00:41:02,480 --> 00:41:05,040
He was mostly
just typing along in the chat.

361
00:41:06,280 --> 00:41:07,919
And then we did ask him to also,

362
00:41:07,920 --> 00:41:12,079
"Just join us in the voice channel
and we'll talk together,"

363
00:41:12,080 --> 00:41:13,160
but he refused.

364
00:41:23,560 --> 00:41:27,559
Well, I just sort of pictured him
like one of my fellow students,

365
00:41:27,560 --> 00:41:29,919
because he was, you know, around my age.

366
00:41:29,920 --> 00:41:33,359
You know, being in high school,
walking through the hallways, um...

367
00:41:33,360 --> 00:41:36,319
Those kinds of things,
and, like, after school,

368
00:41:36,320 --> 00:41:39,399
I figured he'd to go into the city center
with a couple of friends,

369
00:41:39,400 --> 00:41:40,840
visit game stores.

370
00:41:47,000 --> 00:41:49,919
We shared the same interests,
we were online every evening,

371
00:41:49,920 --> 00:41:53,479
just talking, roleplaying,
just having fun.

372
00:41:53,480 --> 00:41:56,799
I would play into the night.

373
00:41:56,800 --> 00:41:59,280
And at some point,
my grades did start to suffer.

374
00:42:01,000 --> 00:42:05,280
There were lots of fights going on
between me, my mother, and my dad.

375
00:42:06,640 --> 00:42:10,359
They said, "Your grades are dropping.
We don't want you to fail school."

376
00:42:10,360 --> 00:42:14,400
"It's not good for you to just sit inside.
You should be active."

377
00:42:15,120 --> 00:42:17,399
My mother going, "You should log off now,

378
00:42:17,400 --> 00:42:22,039
or else I will pull the wires
out of the router to cut the connection,"

379
00:42:22,040 --> 00:42:24,959
and I was like, "No, no,
I just need to play a little bit more."

380
00:42:24,960 --> 00:42:26,960
"I'll just log off in half an hour."

381
00:42:28,520 --> 00:42:29,880
Which, of course, I didn't.

382
00:42:33,560 --> 00:42:36,480
And eventually that led up
to them taking away my computer.

383
00:42:41,800 --> 00:42:46,279
I tried to tell them, "But now I can't
tell my friends that I'm not coming."

384
00:42:46,280 --> 00:42:49,320
"Can I at least have it back
to let them know about that?"

385
00:42:50,480 --> 00:42:53,800
And they said, "They don't need to know,
'cause they're not your real friends."

386
00:42:54,760 --> 00:42:57,279
"Why do you care about them?
You've never met these people."

387
00:42:57,280 --> 00:42:58,759
"You've never seen them."

388
00:42:58,760 --> 00:43:00,400
It was very painful.

389
00:43:06,680 --> 00:43:08,239
So I got depressed.

390
00:43:08,240 --> 00:43:09,400
Um...

391
00:43:11,840 --> 00:43:16,080
I couldn't really figure out reasons
anymore to get out of bed.

392
00:43:20,080 --> 00:43:22,840
"What am I living for?"

393
00:43:25,200 --> 00:43:26,760
Those kind of thoughts.

394
00:43:44,240 --> 00:43:47,159
Eventually, I was sort of like,
"Okay, I've been gone a while now."

395
00:43:47,160 --> 00:43:49,919
"I should find a way to let them
at least know what happened,"

396
00:43:49,920 --> 00:43:54,520
then I figured I could go to the library,
because there was a computer there.

397
00:44:01,520 --> 00:44:03,480
<i>Hey, Lis!
Great to hear from you again.</i>

398
00:44:05,240 --> 00:44:07,760
Well, first off,
he asked me how I was doing.

399
00:44:09,320 --> 00:44:12,840
I told him,
"Okay. I'm coping and holding on."

400
00:44:14,520 --> 00:44:18,759
<i>Would be nice to talk to you again,
so I hope to hear from you later today.</i>

401
00:44:18,760 --> 00:44:21,040
<i>If you can't show up, I will understand.</i>

402
00:44:25,840 --> 00:44:30,439
Ibelin was a really,
really big support pillar, shall I say,

403
00:44:30,440 --> 00:44:33,039
because it was a friend
that I could be open with

404
00:44:33,040 --> 00:44:35,080
about all the things that was going on.

405
00:44:38,520 --> 00:44:41,760
<i>Hello again, Merry Christmas.</i>

406
00:44:42,880 --> 00:44:44,599
I think it's part of the things

407
00:44:44,600 --> 00:44:48,200
that got me out of that depression
that I was in.

408
00:44:49,960 --> 00:44:53,040
<i>Hey, Lis.
So how has your summer been so far?</i>

409
00:44:54,240 --> 00:44:56,160
<i>Thanks for all the talks we had this year.</i>

410
00:45:00,240 --> 00:45:03,320
<i>Here's a little something I wrote today.
Hope you like it.</i>

411
00:45:08,800 --> 00:45:11,119
<i>Dear Mr. and Mrs. Roovers,</i>

412
00:45:11,120 --> 00:45:14,640
<i>you might not know me,
but I'm a friend of your daughter Lisette.</i>

413
00:45:15,360 --> 00:45:17,960
<i>Me and several other friends
are concerned about her.</i>

414
00:45:18,480 --> 00:45:21,160
<i>We heard her computer
was taken away from her.</i>

415
00:45:23,320 --> 00:45:25,999
Eventually, he indeed wrote
the letter to my parents

416
00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:29,559
asking if they could
please return the PC to me

417
00:45:29,560 --> 00:45:31,800
and have a good talk about it.

418
00:45:33,120 --> 00:45:35,640
And he told me to show it to my parents,
which I did.

419
00:45:41,320 --> 00:45:44,599
<i>I am not sure why you are
not allowing her to play these games,</i>

420
00:45:44,600 --> 00:45:47,560
<i>but there has to be some other way
to solve this conflict.</i>

421
00:45:48,080 --> 00:45:51,800
<i>Don't keep pushing her away.
Just try to come to an agreement.</i>

422
00:45:54,280 --> 00:45:57,399
<i>All I ask of you is that you consider
what you are doing,</i>

423
00:45:57,400 --> 00:46:00,560
<i>and you try to come up with
a solution everyone can live with,</i>

424
00:46:01,160 --> 00:46:03,240
<i>because this is not the right thing to do.</i>

425
00:46:04,280 --> 00:46:08,479
I think it was just
such a weird thing for them to have,

426
00:46:08,480 --> 00:46:11,039
essentially a letter that's written

427
00:46:11,040 --> 00:46:13,279
by someone who's concerned
about your daughter,

428
00:46:13,280 --> 00:46:15,480
who lives, like, three countries away.

429
00:46:17,040 --> 00:46:19,039
<i>I think she's a great person,</i>

430
00:46:19,040 --> 00:46:21,360
<i>and I consider her
one of my close friends.</i>

431
00:46:22,440 --> 00:46:26,040
<i>From a worried friend, Mats Steen, Norway.</i>

432
00:46:43,400 --> 00:46:45,800
Yes!

433
00:47:07,560 --> 00:47:10,480
I drew
Ibelin holding Rumour close.

434
00:47:15,960 --> 00:47:18,840
It says, "Warning, cuteness alert,"
and a little smiley.

435
00:47:21,880 --> 00:47:23,920
So I sent the picture to Mats.

436
00:47:31,080 --> 00:47:34,760
<i>I was overwhelmed.
Truly an amazing gift.</i>

437
00:47:35,800 --> 00:47:37,840
<i>It always brings a smile to my face.</i>

438
00:47:44,960 --> 00:47:46,639
<i>In this other world,</i>

439
00:47:46,640 --> 00:47:49,520
<i>a girl wouldn't see a wheelchair
or anything different.</i>

440
00:47:50,160 --> 00:47:52,839
<i>They would get my soul, heart, and mind,</i>

441
00:47:52,840 --> 00:47:55,520
<i>conveniently placed
in a handsome, strong body.</i>

442
00:47:56,280 --> 00:47:58,639
- It's Mats himself.
- Yeah, yeah.

443
00:47:58,640 --> 00:48:01,039
<i>In real life, I've grown weaker,</i>

444
00:48:01,040 --> 00:48:04,720
<i>and can't even eat much of the delicious
Christmas dinner like I used to.</i>

445
00:48:09,880 --> 00:48:12,200
Powdered sugar and banana.

446
00:48:12,960 --> 00:48:13,880
It's Mia's smoothie.

447
00:48:14,960 --> 00:48:17,640
<i>It feels odd
to just watch the others eat.</i>

448
00:48:18,360 --> 00:48:20,360
<i>Oh, how I miss those flavours.</i>

449
00:48:24,920 --> 00:48:27,959
<i>You see, I have my own food device</i>

450
00:48:27,960 --> 00:48:29,920
<i>pumping liquid food into me.</i>

451
00:48:35,560 --> 00:48:37,560
<i>I graduated with flying colours.</i>

452
00:48:38,360 --> 00:48:39,720
<i>I was among the best.</i>

453
00:48:40,960 --> 00:48:44,080
<i>But I have no job to go to,
nowhere I should be.</i>

454
00:48:46,200 --> 00:48:49,720
<i>My dream is to be able to work,
feel valued, and respected.</i>

455
00:49:00,400 --> 00:49:02,600
<i>♪ You gotta dig ♪</i>

456
00:49:03,800 --> 00:49:07,920
<i>♪ Your body
And your head down in the snow ♪</i>

457
00:49:10,840 --> 00:49:13,760
<i>♪ You gotta tie ♪</i>

458
00:49:14,760 --> 00:49:19,000
<i>♪ Your scarf around my pole
To let them know... ♪</i>

459
00:49:22,200 --> 00:49:26,520
Before I got to know Ibelin,
I had seen him around.

460
00:49:28,720 --> 00:49:31,559
Every single day
when he logged into the game,

461
00:49:31,560 --> 00:49:33,640
he ran the same route

462
00:49:34,520 --> 00:49:35,639
about half an hour.

463
00:49:35,640 --> 00:49:40,960
<i>♪ We gotta move our fingers
And our toes and we'll be fine... ♪</i>

464
00:49:45,480 --> 00:49:47,400
And then we started to talk.

465
00:49:48,400 --> 00:49:53,080
He told me he had a job
and he worked early hours every day.

466
00:49:55,000 --> 00:49:59,480
Then again, he was always gaming
in the early hours every day.

467
00:50:01,200 --> 00:50:03,520
So you're not trusting Starlight...

468
00:50:04,480 --> 00:50:08,240
He wasn't so keen on sharing
what he was doing as work.

469
00:50:09,080 --> 00:50:12,439
I was thinking, "Is there anything wrong?"

470
00:50:12,440 --> 00:50:14,320
But I didn't want to pry.

471
00:50:17,280 --> 00:50:22,080
So I started to share things
of my own life with him.

472
00:50:31,720 --> 00:50:35,519
I couldn't really connect
really good with my son as I wanted to

473
00:50:35,520 --> 00:50:38,159
because he has autism, and...

474
00:50:38,160 --> 00:50:42,240
I felt like a bad mom because
I couldn't make my son feel good.

475
00:50:42,800 --> 00:50:45,960
It was really hard.

476
00:50:51,720 --> 00:50:56,720
I got four years
where I couldn't get myself to go out.

477
00:50:57,680 --> 00:51:00,400
I didn't even go to school.

478
00:51:01,840 --> 00:51:03,879
I just stayed home.

479
00:51:03,880 --> 00:51:08,760
I'd lie in bed
to just keep everything away from me.

480
00:51:13,640 --> 00:51:16,199
He hated if you touched him.

481
00:51:16,200 --> 00:51:19,759
When I was going to bed,
my mum would want a hug from me.

482
00:51:19,760 --> 00:51:22,079
- And I was just like...
- "No."

483
00:51:22,080 --> 00:51:24,560
Yeah, "Why?"

484
00:51:26,720 --> 00:51:31,439
And I think that was because
I didn't have a connection with my mum.

485
00:51:31,440 --> 00:51:33,600
And I tried to explain that to Ibelin.

486
00:51:35,120 --> 00:51:37,560
And then he... he went quiet.

487
00:51:44,600 --> 00:51:48,759
And he said, "Well,
try and connect with him through gaming,

488
00:51:48,760 --> 00:51:51,640
because you have seen he likes to play."

489
00:51:52,840 --> 00:51:55,440
And then I was like,
"Well, he's got a point."

490
00:52:04,640 --> 00:52:07,160
I do remember
I had quite a lot of fun playing.

491
00:52:09,960 --> 00:52:14,040
And I feel almost like
he was part of the family.

492
00:52:15,920 --> 00:52:17,879
But there are solutions
to most things.

493
00:52:17,880 --> 00:52:22,480
I do remember when I learned
that I could hug people in-game.

494
00:52:27,080 --> 00:52:29,159
Mikkel, he came in one day,

495
00:52:29,160 --> 00:52:32,720
and he said, "Well, Mum,
there's an emote in the game."

496
00:52:34,280 --> 00:52:36,200
"You can have a hug like that."

497
00:52:36,760 --> 00:52:40,200
I was really hoping
that my mum would accept that.

498
00:52:58,920 --> 00:53:02,359
I felt... happy,

499
00:53:02,360 --> 00:53:05,959
because I could give what my mum wants,

500
00:53:05,960 --> 00:53:08,520
without feeling uncomfortable.

501
00:53:12,400 --> 00:53:15,400
I told Ibelin, "What have you done?"

502
00:53:16,880 --> 00:53:21,360
And he was like, "Well, isn't it nice?
It's a new way to connect with your son."

503
00:53:22,080 --> 00:53:26,719
And I was like, "Okay, that's true,
but I will still want a hug in real life."

504
00:53:26,720 --> 00:53:29,960
And he said,
"Well, you can work towards that."

505
00:53:33,600 --> 00:53:35,599
That was not very nice of you.

506
00:53:35,600 --> 00:53:37,680
I didn't think
they would come alive.

507
00:53:38,200 --> 00:53:40,520
- What are you doing?
- Falling.

508
00:53:41,120 --> 00:53:45,000
- Still? No.
- No, I fell to the ground.

509
00:53:45,760 --> 00:53:47,400
It helped a lot.

510
00:53:48,800 --> 00:53:53,359
He could tell me things that he normally
couldn't tell me in the game.

511
00:53:53,360 --> 00:53:56,479
- But school said it all went okay?
- Yeah.

512
00:53:56,480 --> 00:54:00,799
It was the first time in my life
that I could feel love

513
00:54:00,800 --> 00:54:02,519
and start to understand love.

514
00:54:02,520 --> 00:54:04,999
And that was one of those...

515
00:54:05,000 --> 00:54:07,999
the heavens opened up
and everything was just,

516
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:11,400
"Oh!
This is what I have been waiting for."

517
00:54:30,160 --> 00:54:32,279
I just have to say...

518
00:54:32,280 --> 00:54:35,159
And then Ibelin told me that...

519
00:54:35,160 --> 00:54:38,920
Sometimes you have to jump in,
no matter how scary it might seem.

520
00:54:54,960 --> 00:54:56,040
I have a pet.

521
00:54:57,040 --> 00:54:59,639
I call him Wolfie. I really like nature.

522
00:54:59,640 --> 00:55:01,639
You've accomplished
your daily quest.

523
00:55:01,640 --> 00:55:03,240
Five hundred points to you.

524
00:55:04,680 --> 00:55:06,800
Give yourself some credit once in a while.

525
00:55:10,640 --> 00:55:12,800
There are solutions
to most things.

526
00:55:19,680 --> 00:55:20,799
From that time on,

527
00:55:20,800 --> 00:55:23,599
you went actually to school,
each day, you walked to school.

528
00:55:23,600 --> 00:55:25,880
Yeah. Every day.

529
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:32,960
I'll just mess it all up,
and you guys get to try to fix it!

530
00:55:33,640 --> 00:55:37,999
I went from
the most negative person in the world

531
00:55:38,000 --> 00:55:40,600
to a person that could tolerate people.

532
00:55:57,040 --> 00:56:00,000
The word about Ibelin
started to spread around.

533
00:56:04,240 --> 00:56:06,519
And to be honest,
I think the investigator job

534
00:56:06,520 --> 00:56:08,800
was just a way for him
to get to know people.

535
00:56:19,640 --> 00:56:21,680
I hope things will work out.

536
00:56:23,240 --> 00:56:27,480
He was very,
very empathic, intuitive,

537
00:56:28,000 --> 00:56:31,320
very good at knowing what you needed.

538
00:56:33,480 --> 00:56:37,440
I'd been feeling worthless
for months, afraid to reach out to people.

539
00:56:38,880 --> 00:56:40,920
I didn't really have anyone to talk to.

540
00:56:41,800 --> 00:56:43,799
And suddenly he asked me...

541
00:56:43,800 --> 00:56:45,360
"How are you doing?"

542
00:56:45,880 --> 00:56:49,520
And I told him everything.
I told him how terrible I had felt.

543
00:56:50,600 --> 00:56:54,600
Perhaps it does not seem like much,
but it meant the world to me.

544
00:56:57,480 --> 00:56:58,760
I feel with you.

545
00:57:00,200 --> 00:57:04,600
He actually did take an interest
into what you were talking about.

546
00:57:07,320 --> 00:57:11,040
I don't think he ever
even realized how much it meant to me.

547
00:57:19,520 --> 00:57:23,920
Everyone in Starlight was real
excited to have a meet-up in real life

548
00:57:24,720 --> 00:57:26,640
and see each other for the first time.

549
00:57:31,160 --> 00:57:34,440
I was very excited about it
and looking forward to meeting Ibelin...

550
00:57:35,280 --> 00:57:39,959
and just getting to know him
off-screen as well,

551
00:57:39,960 --> 00:57:42,559
and just having those conversations
face-to-face for a change

552
00:57:42,560 --> 00:57:44,520
instead of just text.

553
00:57:47,120 --> 00:57:49,399
I actually asked him,
"Are you also coming?"

554
00:57:49,400 --> 00:57:51,520
"Because everyone else is coming."

555
00:58:04,400 --> 00:58:07,880
But he said "no," that, uh,
he had, I think, different things to do.

556
00:58:11,360 --> 00:58:12,880
And I was disappointed.

557
00:58:25,120 --> 00:58:28,839
I got to travel to a country
by myself for the first time,

558
00:58:28,840 --> 00:58:30,560
which I thought was fantastic.

559
00:58:36,240 --> 00:58:38,159
I hadn't seen anyone.

560
00:58:38,160 --> 00:58:41,880
So for me, it was all fresh faces
and no one that I recognized.

561
00:58:57,400 --> 00:59:01,840
We were sad that Ibelin
could not come to Denmark himself.

562
00:59:07,240 --> 00:59:09,279
So I wrote to tell him,

563
00:59:09,280 --> 00:59:13,040
"We have voice chat going on.
Do you want to join?"

564
00:59:13,840 --> 00:59:18,720
And the reply I got was "no,"
he doesn't want to join this voice chat.

565
00:59:25,400 --> 00:59:28,680
So I pulled out my camera
and started taking pictures

566
00:59:29,320 --> 00:59:31,400
so we could share that with Ibelin.

567
00:59:41,160 --> 00:59:43,360
Hey, y'all!

568
01:00:03,960 --> 01:00:06,680
<i>Love has always been
a tricky subject for me.</i>

569
01:00:07,920 --> 01:00:10,160
<i>It feels like it's just not meant for me.</i>

570
01:00:14,360 --> 01:00:16,279
<i>And she did live in another country,</i>

571
01:00:16,280 --> 01:00:18,600
<i>so part of me
knew nothing would ever happen.</i>

572
01:00:19,200 --> 01:00:22,360
<i>Wheelchairs and all that
tend to make things difficult.</i>

573
01:00:26,520 --> 01:00:29,119
<i>These dark thoughts
just tried to drag me down.</i>

574
01:00:29,120 --> 01:00:30,360
<i>Making excuses.</i>

575
01:00:31,520 --> 01:00:33,880
<i>Online, I can at least
do all the things I want.</i>

576
01:00:45,640 --> 01:00:47,400
My name is Ibelin.

577
01:00:48,760 --> 01:00:50,279
Ibelin Redmoore.

578
01:00:50,280 --> 01:00:53,440
I'm staying at The Poison Tip Dagger
at the moment.

579
01:00:54,560 --> 01:00:58,279
You wouldn't believe how good it feels
to jump from one rooftop to another.

580
01:00:58,280 --> 01:01:00,520
Well, things could quickly
take a bad turn.

581
01:01:05,360 --> 01:01:06,480
That is awesome.

582
01:01:31,760 --> 01:01:34,839
I was walking around
in Stormwind,

583
01:01:34,840 --> 01:01:37,840
and then I noticed that Ibelin was nearby.

584
01:02:32,080 --> 01:02:33,519
It was pretty devastating,

585
01:02:33,520 --> 01:02:37,240
because I think I felt betrayed
that he just hadn't told me beforehand.

586
01:02:38,600 --> 01:02:42,639
You know, I figure out
when I just come back into the game, um...

587
01:02:42,640 --> 01:02:44,520
so I was very upset.

588
01:03:11,320 --> 01:03:14,320
He didn't also quite understand
why I was upset with him for this.

589
01:03:16,520 --> 01:03:19,200
I lost the spark,
I felt I was choking.

590
01:03:20,720 --> 01:03:22,520
Right now, I feel better off on my own.

591
01:03:23,320 --> 01:03:24,360
Unchained.

592
01:03:26,920 --> 01:03:28,240
I'm not good at commitment.

593
01:03:28,880 --> 01:03:30,800
I can't explain why, I just...

594
01:03:31,320 --> 01:03:34,280
I just shake things off and move along,

595
01:03:35,840 --> 01:03:37,080
like I've always done.

596
01:03:52,800 --> 01:03:55,920
<i>In</i> World of Warcraft,
<i>I've flirted and been with several women,</i>

597
01:03:57,440 --> 01:03:58,960
<i>but it can never be the same.</i>

598
01:04:09,280 --> 01:04:11,240
<i>I never told her about my feelings.</i>

599
01:04:13,960 --> 01:04:15,560
<i>I remember thinking,</i>

600
01:04:16,360 --> 01:04:18,200
<i>"If only I wasn't handicapped."</i>

601
01:04:19,200 --> 01:04:20,840
<i>It was always my excuse.</i>

602
01:04:27,960 --> 01:04:29,920
<i>Why was I born with this condition?</i>

603
01:04:31,120 --> 01:04:35,120
<i>My body is starting to feel more and more
like a prison holding me back.</i>

604
01:04:37,920 --> 01:04:41,760
<i>Using a computer has become
more difficult the last few years.</i>

605
01:04:42,680 --> 01:04:45,120
<i>There's always one button I can't reach.</i>

606
01:04:53,800 --> 01:04:56,880
<i>Of course, this button
has to be used at some point.</i>

607
01:05:01,000 --> 01:05:02,320
Help us!

608
01:05:02,920 --> 01:05:04,680
Come on, please!

609
01:05:08,520 --> 01:05:11,120
Are you going to stand there all day?

610
01:05:16,960 --> 01:05:18,640
What is wrong with you?

611
01:05:20,760 --> 01:05:22,400
You are worthless!

612
01:05:31,840 --> 01:05:33,959
I'm Erica, by the way.

613
01:05:33,960 --> 01:05:37,840
Thinks she'd be all safe up there.
No idea why someone would...

614
01:05:39,720 --> 01:05:42,120
Agility is very important for a rogue.

615
01:05:44,160 --> 01:05:46,880
<i>Damn, what is wrong with you?</i>

616
01:05:48,240 --> 01:05:50,720
<i>Ibelin, are you stupid?</i>

617
01:06:00,160 --> 01:06:02,159
I was never a big fan of him.

618
01:06:02,160 --> 01:06:04,600
He's another firecracker
with a nasty temper.

619
01:06:08,000 --> 01:06:09,800
I don't trust the bastard a second.

620
01:06:10,880 --> 01:06:13,039
<i>It's a challenge,
holding my tongue.</i>

621
01:06:13,040 --> 01:06:16,040
He's an old criminal, old suspect.

622
01:06:16,640 --> 01:06:19,280
I haven't met
a more arrogant person in my life.

623
01:06:20,240 --> 01:06:23,560
<i>I never set out to be that guy,
yet here I am.</i>

624
01:06:34,080 --> 01:06:37,399
Ibelin, you need to leave it
and calm down.

625
01:06:37,400 --> 01:06:41,079
You'll get in trouble
if you continue on talking like this.

626
01:06:41,080 --> 01:06:44,080
Your words start to hurt other people.
You need to stop.

627
01:06:57,120 --> 01:07:00,399
...trying to be a leader
of those who was there.

628
01:07:00,400 --> 01:07:02,520
At least to fight for Starlight...

629
01:07:17,360 --> 01:07:18,600
It's not fair!

630
01:07:25,440 --> 01:07:29,600
Her anger, resentment.
She told me to fuck off a couple of times!

631
01:07:31,080 --> 01:07:33,239
You lack much of the humanity

632
01:07:33,240 --> 01:07:35,719
and compassion
a good leader must also have.

633
01:07:35,720 --> 01:07:38,880
Maybe you get the job done,
but at what price?

634
01:07:40,200 --> 01:07:42,360
I can't stand this anymore.

635
01:07:50,240 --> 01:07:52,600
I felt hurt by it.

636
01:08:00,000 --> 01:08:02,440
And I told him,
"Well, you actually hurt me."

637
01:08:04,040 --> 01:08:07,040
"You don't care about Starlight?"

638
01:08:10,320 --> 01:08:15,959
And he said, "Well, it's just stupid rules
in a stupid guild in a stupid game."

639
01:08:15,960 --> 01:08:18,799
"I don't want to play
this stupid thing anymore."

640
01:08:18,800 --> 01:08:21,040
And then
he actually logged off that night.

641
01:08:22,360 --> 01:08:25,120
And I was like, "Oh, my God."

642
01:08:33,360 --> 01:08:35,960
And I didn't
talk to him for a year.

643
01:08:44,840 --> 01:08:49,800
His relationship drama came to the point
where it became a stressor.

644
01:08:50,320 --> 01:08:55,280
He didn't have the proper means
to tackle it and navigate it well.

645
01:08:56,280 --> 01:08:58,999
And it started to influence

646
01:08:59,000 --> 01:09:02,760
which events he would go to,
which events the other would go to,

647
01:09:03,280 --> 01:09:05,519
how people spoke about each other.

648
01:09:05,520 --> 01:09:07,440
And people started taking sides.

649
01:09:12,640 --> 01:09:16,680
Other members in the guild
started to take a distance away from him.

650
01:09:17,440 --> 01:09:22,160
They didn't want the risk
of being involved in these conflicts.

651
01:09:28,120 --> 01:09:30,559
And it pisses me off
to spend 20 minutes...

652
01:09:30,560 --> 01:09:34,479
And you also had people
who were coming to us and saying,

653
01:09:34,480 --> 01:09:37,720
"Hey, this is the third time
he's created a fight."

654
01:09:38,480 --> 01:09:40,320
So I needed to talk to Ibelin.

655
01:09:45,720 --> 01:09:50,119
So I wrote to Ibelin one day and asked,
"Would it be okay if I just came over?"

656
01:09:50,120 --> 01:09:53,480
We're both living in Oslo,
it would just be a short bus drive.

657
01:09:57,000 --> 01:09:59,120
And the reply I got was very, very sharp.

658
01:10:00,280 --> 01:10:03,600
No, he don't want to have a visitor over.

659
01:10:13,600 --> 01:10:15,400
<i>Sometimes I think I can't breathe.</i>

660
01:10:21,320 --> 01:10:23,359
Could you hold this button?

661
01:10:23,360 --> 01:10:25,919
<i>Luckily,
there's always an assistant nearby</i>

662
01:10:25,920 --> 01:10:27,560
<i>to soothe me when this happens.</i>

663
01:10:31,120 --> 01:10:33,800
<i>I have 11 of them
working full-time with me.</i>

664
01:10:38,200 --> 01:10:41,400
<i>One day, my chest
was making awful wheezing noises.</i>

665
01:10:42,920 --> 01:10:45,480
<i>I had never experienced
anything like this.</i>

666
01:10:49,240 --> 01:10:53,360
<i>I couldn't breathe,
and I started thrashing about in panic.</i>

667
01:10:59,240 --> 01:11:02,519
<i>I remembered my mother's
cries of panic as I passed out</i>

668
01:11:02,520 --> 01:11:04,520
<i>before I got to the ambulance.</i>

669
01:11:12,760 --> 01:11:15,920
<i>For some reason,
everything was white and cold...</i>

670
01:11:17,920 --> 01:11:19,840
<i>like the mountains of the Himalayas.</i>

671
01:11:26,040 --> 01:11:28,560
<i>It might have been my mind
playing tricks on me,</i>

672
01:11:29,080 --> 01:11:30,960
<i>but that was where I was.</i>

673
01:11:43,120 --> 01:11:44,480
<i>I remember thinking,</i>

674
01:11:45,440 --> 01:11:46,440
<i>"This is it."</i>

675
01:11:47,680 --> 01:11:48,760
<i>"This is the end."</i>

676
01:12:00,360 --> 01:12:03,080
<i>Finally, my eyes opened
in the emergency room.</i>

677
01:12:05,160 --> 01:12:07,999
<i>This was one of the hardest things
I've been through,</i>

678
01:12:08,000 --> 01:12:09,720
<i>even if I've been through a lot.</i>

679
01:12:18,920 --> 01:12:20,560
Death would have to wait.

680
01:12:56,160 --> 01:12:59,359
Ibelin started to have
periods of time where he logged out,

681
01:12:59,360 --> 01:13:04,120
and I didn't see him logging in
to the game again for a long time.

682
01:13:09,160 --> 01:13:12,800
There was that kind of nagging feeling
something was wrong.

683
01:13:17,040 --> 01:13:20,439
He would just say,
"I've been on a vacation."

684
01:13:20,440 --> 01:13:21,880
I was like, "Hmm."

685
01:13:22,880 --> 01:13:24,880
"There's something he's not telling me."

686
01:13:27,320 --> 01:13:31,079
I remember asking him once,
"Have you been in prison? Or..."

687
01:13:31,080 --> 01:13:33,720
He was like,
"No, I have been on a vacation."

688
01:13:34,680 --> 01:13:35,919
And I was like,

689
01:13:35,920 --> 01:13:38,560
"Did you go to the vacation
in the hospital?"

690
01:13:43,160 --> 01:13:45,680
He didn't respond to me for five minutes.

691
01:13:55,800 --> 01:13:59,320
Then he responded to me,
"Sorry, I just had to go to the loo."

692
01:14:00,800 --> 01:14:01,879
And then I told him,

693
01:14:01,880 --> 01:14:04,679
"Did you go to a vacation
in the hospital?"

694
01:14:04,680 --> 01:14:06,519
"Oh, no, no, no, not the hospital,"

695
01:14:06,520 --> 01:14:10,079
and I think there were ten no's after.

696
01:14:10,080 --> 01:14:12,640
"No, no, no, no, no, not the hospital."

697
01:14:14,560 --> 01:14:17,560
I wrote to him,
"Did I hit the nail there?"

698
01:14:18,920 --> 01:14:21,400
The only thing he wrote was, "Good night."

699
01:14:36,360 --> 01:14:40,080
<i>I just had to get out of that city,
get away from it all.</i>

700
01:14:53,600 --> 01:14:55,560
<i>Games are my sanctuary.</i>

701
01:14:56,680 --> 01:14:59,840
<i>I am safe here, feel valued and respected.</i>

702
01:15:01,400 --> 01:15:03,240
<i>Is my sanctuary threatened?</i>

703
01:15:04,680 --> 01:15:07,280
<i>Should I not be able
to game anymore either?</i>

704
01:15:23,160 --> 01:15:26,680
<i>Guess I'm trying to run away
from the one thing I can never escape.</i>

705
01:15:28,120 --> 01:15:29,120
<i>Myself.</i>

706
01:16:01,280 --> 01:16:04,400
And then he said,
"I would like to tell you something."

707
01:16:07,000 --> 01:16:11,800
"Well, I'm actually in a wheelchair.
I'm only able to move my fingers."

708
01:16:15,640 --> 01:16:19,840
"I have Duchenne,
so I don't know when I'm going to die."

709
01:16:35,760 --> 01:16:39,040
And he was like,
"I don't want you to pity me."

710
01:16:44,640 --> 01:16:47,319
"You are the only one who know,

711
01:16:47,320 --> 01:16:49,399
and you're the only one who should know,

712
01:16:49,400 --> 01:16:52,680
because I do not want
anyone to know that I'm sick."

713
01:17:00,240 --> 01:17:03,440
I told him, "Well, what is the fear?"

714
01:17:11,600 --> 01:17:14,880
And he said,
"Well, I fear I don't matter."

715
01:17:16,160 --> 01:17:18,199
"You have to keep in mind,

716
01:17:18,200 --> 01:17:21,120
I'm here in my apartment,

717
01:17:21,640 --> 01:17:24,120
with my Duchenne."

718
01:17:25,600 --> 01:17:28,440
"I'm really afraid of dying. I can't...

719
01:17:33,040 --> 01:17:36,560
go on and die
without having mattered to anyone."

720
01:17:41,200 --> 01:17:42,399
I told him,

721
01:17:42,400 --> 01:17:45,959
"I think you have made a big impact
on a lot of people's lives,"

722
01:17:45,960 --> 01:17:47,480
and he said, "No."

723
01:17:51,920 --> 01:17:55,920
And I was like,
"You have mattered to me and Mikkel."

724
01:18:04,000 --> 01:18:07,319
I don't think I would have
such a great life as I have now

725
01:18:07,320 --> 01:18:08,840
if it wasn't for him.

726
01:18:10,200 --> 01:18:11,719
If it wasn't for him,

727
01:18:11,720 --> 01:18:15,400
I wouldn't have such a strong relationship
as I have now with my mum,

728
01:18:16,000 --> 01:18:20,679
and I probably wouldn't be drawing today
or go to school.

729
01:18:20,680 --> 01:18:26,600
I think I would just be someone
who was just sitting in their room,

730
01:18:27,120 --> 01:18:31,720
hating myself every day
because I couldn't understand

731
01:18:32,240 --> 01:18:35,240
why I'm so different and everything.

732
01:18:38,120 --> 01:18:39,120
So, yeah.

733
01:18:41,240 --> 01:18:44,240
That hit a lot harder on me
than I thought it would.

734
01:18:47,600 --> 01:18:51,600
I told him
how much he meant to us. Um...

735
01:19:02,160 --> 01:19:03,679
And then he said,

736
01:19:03,680 --> 01:19:06,240
"Well, that made me feel
really nice inside."

737
01:19:06,760 --> 01:19:08,320
"I'm grateful for that."

738
01:19:10,480 --> 01:19:13,800
And then I told him,
"Well, of course you matter to all of us."

739
01:19:16,520 --> 01:19:21,280
Then I started to list a lot of names
that he had helped.

740
01:19:22,360 --> 01:19:24,639
And then he just wrote back,

741
01:19:24,640 --> 01:19:27,320
"This is too emotional for me."

742
01:19:28,680 --> 01:19:32,759
And I was like, "Well, you need to be
emotional as well from time to time."

743
01:19:32,760 --> 01:19:35,240
"Then you know
you have mattered to people."

744
01:19:41,000 --> 01:19:44,840
"And I really wish
that you would tell others as well."

745
01:20:21,760 --> 01:20:23,240
<i>I still think of her.</i>

746
01:20:36,280 --> 01:20:38,440
<i>Weird how it is with your first crush.</i>

747
01:20:50,120 --> 01:20:53,880
<i>This blog is about my life
as a young, handicapped man in Norway.</i>

748
01:20:58,480 --> 01:21:02,560
<i>I was born with a muscular disease
known as Duchenne muscular dystrophy.</i>

749
01:21:04,880 --> 01:21:08,320
<i>It slowly reduces my muscles,
making me gradually weaker.</i>

750
01:21:09,720 --> 01:21:12,560
<i>I could walk once,
but now I depend on a wheelchair.</i>

751
01:21:13,960 --> 01:21:14,840
<i>There.</i>

752
01:21:15,400 --> 01:21:17,160
<i>Good, we got that out of the way.</i>

753
01:21:22,520 --> 01:21:26,000
<i>I am happy to share my story
and my musings of life with you.</i>

754
01:21:47,120 --> 01:21:49,920
And...
I was mostly shocked reading that.

755
01:21:52,760 --> 01:21:56,720
His muscles are slowly giving out and
it meant that he was going to die soon.

756
01:22:06,920 --> 01:22:09,519
<i>There was something
very exciting about her,</i>

757
01:22:09,520 --> 01:22:12,479
<i>her humour, the way she acted,</i>

758
01:22:12,480 --> 01:22:14,160
<i>how she would express herself.</i>

759
01:22:18,440 --> 01:22:20,920
<i>I remember thinking, "If only..."</i>

760
01:22:22,000 --> 01:22:23,720
<i>"If only I wasn't handicapped."</i>

761
01:22:25,600 --> 01:22:29,599
I can very much understand that
you don't want to be judged differently,

762
01:22:29,600 --> 01:22:32,599
or that people start treating
you differently once they find out,

763
01:22:32,600 --> 01:22:35,360
and that can be a seriously legit fear.

764
01:22:45,920 --> 01:22:50,999
But at the same time I confided a lot of
my own problems with him over the years,

765
01:22:51,000 --> 01:22:55,159
and he never confided in me the same way,
which feels a bit...

766
01:22:55,160 --> 01:22:56,359
a bit wrong.

767
01:22:56,360 --> 01:23:01,520
It feels weird
to not be trusted the same way around.

768
01:23:33,120 --> 01:23:34,439
And I was like,

769
01:23:34,440 --> 01:23:36,840
"Okay, I'm not sure
how to respond to this."

770
01:23:48,400 --> 01:23:53,200
And, um, "But you're still you,
so nothing changed there for me."

771
01:24:25,000 --> 01:24:28,719
So apart from that,
nothing really changed for me, 'cause...

772
01:24:28,720 --> 01:24:32,680
well, we just mainly
went back to just normal.

773
01:25:35,080 --> 01:25:38,960
First, Mats wrote an apology
for hurting others in the community.

774
01:25:40,080 --> 01:25:43,920
I'm an emotional man,
and I often follow my heart.

775
01:25:46,720 --> 01:25:47,880
I am sorry.

776
01:25:56,280 --> 01:26:00,240
Later, he also decided
to share the blog he had been writing on.

777
01:26:07,600 --> 01:26:11,240
And reading that,
one of the things that hurt the most

778
01:26:12,040 --> 01:26:15,960
was not being able to have been there
for him the way he had been there for us.

779
01:26:22,640 --> 01:26:27,360
He was met with warmth.
He was met with respect.

780
01:26:31,680 --> 01:26:36,159
And I think this gave him the support

781
01:26:36,160 --> 01:26:42,120
and this feeling of safety he
needed to share even more.

782
01:26:49,120 --> 01:26:51,559
<i>A young man in his early 20s</i>

783
01:26:51,560 --> 01:26:53,919
<i>got in touch
with the central office in Oslo.</i>

784
01:26:53,920 --> 01:26:57,679
He agreed
to participate in an information video

785
01:26:57,680 --> 01:26:59,800
about specialized equipment.

786
01:27:01,400 --> 01:27:04,079
The video was shown all over Norway

787
01:27:04,080 --> 01:27:06,519
and used to show how specialized equipment

788
01:27:06,520 --> 01:27:09,239
could aid people in a similar situation.

789
01:27:09,240 --> 01:27:11,000
...to play on a computer.

790
01:27:13,080 --> 01:27:17,160
The entire documentary was
done in secret from his parents,

791
01:27:17,760 --> 01:27:20,559
and that fits with him perfectly.

792
01:27:20,560 --> 01:27:23,879
When he has that determination,
when he has decided,

793
01:27:23,880 --> 01:27:27,199
"Let's not be stopped or bothered
by something as inconsequential

794
01:27:27,200 --> 01:27:29,519
as the parents
getting to know about this."

795
01:27:29,520 --> 01:27:32,080
"It's much better to just get it done."

796
01:28:35,000 --> 01:28:37,600
They left their email
in the blog post.

797
01:28:38,680 --> 01:28:41,600
I couldn't really express

798
01:28:42,760 --> 01:28:43,760
how...

799
01:28:44,600 --> 01:28:49,759
you know, how to tell them what their
son meant to me over all these years,

800
01:28:49,760 --> 01:28:52,799
so I didn't really write
a very extensive email.

801
01:28:52,800 --> 01:28:55,680
I think I only wrote,
like, two paragraphs to them.

802
01:28:56,200 --> 01:28:57,200
Um...

803
01:28:57,920 --> 01:29:00,999
Just trying to tell them,

804
01:29:01,000 --> 01:29:03,679
"Okay, your son was a fantastic person."

805
01:29:03,680 --> 01:29:07,600
"And I'm really happy
to have known him, and, uh..."

806
01:29:09,560 --> 01:29:14,720
It very, very much
sucked that he was gone.

807
01:29:21,960 --> 01:29:24,240
"Dear Robert, Trude, and Mia."

808
01:29:25,280 --> 01:29:28,920
"Mats was a real friend to me."

809
01:29:41,440 --> 01:29:43,719
"Despite his challenges,

810
01:29:43,720 --> 01:29:47,520
he still found the strength
to be there for us."

811
01:29:51,400 --> 01:29:57,280
"What mattered to Mats was being able
to spread joy in our lives."

812
01:30:00,160 --> 01:30:06,359
"And stuff I learned from his example
has changed the way I think about life,

813
01:30:06,360 --> 01:30:12,199
and I hope that wherever he is, he knows

814
01:30:12,200 --> 01:30:15,599
he's remembered, and treasured,
and smiling right now."

815
01:30:15,600 --> 01:30:16,520
Mmm.

816
01:30:26,200 --> 01:30:29,879
MATS STEEN
DEEPLY MISSED NEVER FORGOTTEN

817
01:30:29,880 --> 01:30:33,280
When we started
thinking about the gravestone,

818
01:30:34,400 --> 01:30:36,719
what it should say,

819
01:30:36,720 --> 01:30:43,760
we decided that it should be a nice,
somewhat youthful gravestone

820
01:30:45,040 --> 01:30:47,880
that would say, "Mats Steen."

821
01:30:54,840 --> 01:30:57,200
<i>Dear Trude, Robert, and Mia.</i>

822
01:30:59,880 --> 01:31:02,959
<i>I don't know if this is
too much to ask for,</i>

823
01:31:02,960 --> 01:31:04,999
<i>but I wonder when the funeral is,</i>

824
01:31:05,000 --> 01:31:09,800
<i>and if it would be possible for
five of Mats's friends to participate?</i>

825
01:31:11,800 --> 01:31:16,159
<i>We come from Norway, Denmark,
Finland, England, and the Netherlands.</i>

826
01:31:16,160 --> 01:31:19,280
<i>And we would also like to
bring with us our guild tabard.</i>

827
01:31:24,680 --> 01:31:31,760
VESTRE GRAVLUND CHAPEL, OSLO

828
01:31:33,520 --> 01:31:37,759
OUR DEAR SON AND BROTHER.
THANK YOU FOR THE GOOD TIMES.

829
01:31:37,760 --> 01:31:40,320
FOREVER IN OUR HEARTS

830
01:32:10,760 --> 01:32:13,560
I would like to share
one thing with you, Mats.

831
01:32:14,280 --> 01:32:19,479
The biggest pain your mother
and I suffered through life

832
01:32:19,480 --> 01:32:25,239
was that you, because of the illness
we brought you into this world with,

833
01:32:25,240 --> 01:32:29,000
should not experience falling in love.

834
01:32:30,240 --> 01:32:32,360
You should not experience friendship.

835
01:32:33,360 --> 01:32:37,159
You should not experience
social relationships,

836
01:32:37,160 --> 01:32:39,840
and joint activities with others.

837
01:32:41,720 --> 01:32:46,199
You should not experience
contributing to society

838
01:32:46,200 --> 01:32:49,720
and playing a meaningful role
in other people's lives.

839
01:32:50,720 --> 01:32:53,439
This was by far...

840
01:32:53,440 --> 01:32:55,720
...our biggest sorrow.

841
01:32:58,520 --> 01:33:02,519
You proved us wrong.
You proved us so wrong.

842
01:33:02,520 --> 01:33:05,800
And you proved yourself so resourceful.

843
01:33:06,800 --> 01:33:13,319
But it has only been the last week
that we have really got close to realizing

844
01:33:13,320 --> 01:33:16,720
the full impact of the
digital community in his life.

845
01:33:18,040 --> 01:33:24,239
I have the last week calculated
that during your last ten years,

846
01:33:24,240 --> 01:33:29,239
you have spent between
15 and 20 thousand hours

847
01:33:29,240 --> 01:33:31,360
within this digital community.

848
01:33:34,000 --> 01:33:37,120
Mats did fall in love.

849
01:33:39,120 --> 01:33:43,800
Mats was at times accused
for being a womanizer.

850
01:33:45,360 --> 01:33:48,400
And I must admit, being a father,
I'm a bit proud of that.

851
01:33:52,400 --> 01:33:57,479
Mats was, throughout eight
years in the roleplaying world,

852
01:33:57,480 --> 01:34:03,960
a major contributor and a co-author of
a fantastic community called Starlight,

853
01:34:05,240 --> 01:34:08,600
where he got to experience love,

854
01:34:09,400 --> 01:34:10,440
friendship,

855
01:34:10,960 --> 01:34:16,440
and the feeling of making a
difference in other people's lives.

856
01:34:26,480 --> 01:34:30,600
I met Mats in a place where
there is no limitations on his body,

857
01:34:31,760 --> 01:34:34,799
where it does not matter what
you struggle with in your daily life,

858
01:34:34,800 --> 01:34:36,519
the challenges you face.

859
01:34:36,520 --> 01:34:40,720
In a place where he could
choose who we wanted to be.

860
01:34:41,800 --> 01:34:45,559
And many years ago,
Mats choose to reach out to us

861
01:34:45,560 --> 01:34:49,160
and start forming
friendships with us in Starlight.

862
01:34:49,920 --> 01:34:52,920
Those chance encounters
became friendships,

863
01:34:53,920 --> 01:34:57,480
and, ultimately, it led to
five of us being here today.

864
01:34:58,760 --> 01:35:00,600
Mats had a very, very long reach.

865
01:35:04,200 --> 01:35:05,919
And he helped others.

866
01:35:05,920 --> 01:35:08,079
And this is the one thing that rings true

867
01:35:08,080 --> 01:35:10,800
in every story people
have shared about him.

868
01:35:11,400 --> 01:35:13,080
He was selfless and kind.

869
01:35:14,080 --> 01:35:18,960
He was a person who listened, who
welcomed others, and included them.

870
01:35:21,000 --> 01:35:26,120
What mattered to Mats was
being able to spread joy in our lives.

871
01:35:27,400 --> 01:35:31,960
Despite his handicaps, he found
the strength to be there for us.

872
01:35:33,000 --> 01:35:35,160
And the last thing he said to us...

873
01:35:37,000 --> 01:35:38,679
through his family,

874
01:35:38,680 --> 01:35:42,399
"Tell them that I love them, and
that they made my life different."

875
01:35:42,400 --> 01:35:44,000
"Tell them all goodbye."

876
01:35:46,240 --> 01:35:49,840
And, Mats, thank you
for making a difference.

877
01:38:35,480 --> 01:38:42,480
MATS "IBELIN" STEEN
DEEPLY MISSED, NEVER FORGOTTEN

